{x - 2} = \\frac{3}{(x - 1)(x - 2)}.\\]\nFirst, we simplify the denominators and find a common denominator. The common denominator is \\((7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x)(x^2 - 1)(x - 2)\\), but we can simplify it further by noting that \\(x^2 - 1 = (x - 1)(x + 1)\\), so the common denominator is \\((7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x)(x - 1)(x + 1)(x - 2)\\).\n\nRewriting the equation with the common denominator, we get:\n\\[\n\\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1) + (3x^2 - 18x - 22)(x - 7) + 3(7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x)}{(7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x)(x - 1)(x + 1)(x - 2)} = \\frac{3(7 - x)(1 + x)}{(7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x)(x - 1)(x + 1)(x - 2)}.\n\\]\nThe denominators are the same, so we can equate the numerators:\n\\[\n(x - 1)(x + 1) + (3x^2 - 18x - 22)(x - 7) + 3(7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x) = 3(7 - x)(1 + x).\n\\]\nExpanding and simplifying the left-hand side:\n\\[\n(x - 1)(x + 1) = x^2 - 1,\n\\]\n\\[\n(3x^2 - 18x - 22)(x - 7) = 3x^3 - 21x^2 - 18x^2 + 126x - 22x + 154 = 3x^3 - 39x^2 + 104x + 154,\n\\]\n\\[\n3(7 - x)(1 + x)(1 - x) = 3(7 - x)(1 - x^2) = 3(7 - 7x^2 - x + x^3) = 21 - 21x^2 - 3x + 3x^3.\n\\]\nAdding these together:\n\\[\nx^2 - 1 + 3x^3 - 39x^2 + 104x + 154 + 21 - 21x^2 - 3x + 3x^3 = 6x^3 - 59x^2 + 101x + 173.\n\\]\nThe right-hand side is:\n\\[\n3(7 - x)(1 + x) = 3(7 - x + 7x - x^2) = 21 - 3x + 21x - 3x^2 = 21 + 18x - 3x^2.\n\\]\nSetting the numerators equal:\n\\[\n6x^3 - 59x^2 + 101x + 173 = 21 + 18x - 3x^2.\n\\]\nRearranging terms to one side:\n\\[\n6x^3 - 56x^2 + 83x + 152 = 0.\n\\]\nWe can use the Rational Root Theorem to test possible rational roots. Testing \\(x = 4\\):\n\\[\n6(4)^3 - 56(4)^2 + 83(4) + 152 = 6(64) - 56(16) + 332 + 152 = 384 - 896 + 332 + 152 = 72 - 72 = 0.\n\\]\nSo, \\(x = 4\\) is a root. We can use synthetic division to factor out \\(x - 4\\):\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{r|rrrr}\n4 & 6 & -56 & 83 & 152 \\\\\n  &   & 24 & -128 &", "truth": "0", "reward_format": 0.0, "reward_answer": 0.0, "reward_total": 0.0}, {"prompt": "A conversation between User and Assistant. The User asks a question, and the Assis